INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '5f222658-7065-4c88-ad1f-3c63ab6ff3b9',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Flask-SQLAlchemy — Killing N+1 Queries and Surviving Migrations$escape$,
  $escape$Flask-SQLAlchemy's ORM is convenient but silently generates N+1 queries when you touch lazy-loaded relationships. Iterating `Post.query.all()` and accessing `post.author.username` inside the loop fires one SELECT per post — invisible until you hit production scale.

Fix it with SQLAlchemy's eager loading strategies passed via `.options()`. Use `joinedload` for to-one relationships — it emits a single JOIN. Use `selectinload` for to-many — it runs two queries but avoids the cartesian product blowup that `joinedload` causes on collections.

When you need raw query-builder control without model overhead, drop to SQLAlchemy Core directly on `db.session`: `db.session.execute(select(Post).where(Post.published == True))`. Same connection pool, same transaction scope, zero ORM abstraction.

For migrations, Flask-Migrate wraps Alembic under `flask db migrate`. Always audit the auto-generated script before applying — Alembic silently misses index additions on existing columns, `server_default` changes, and constraint renames. Treat `flask db migrate` as a first draft, not ground truth.$escape$,
  $escape$from sqlalchemy.orm import joinedload, selectinload
from sqlalchemy import select

# Bad: N+1 — one query per iteration
posts = Post.query.all()
for p in posts:
    print(p.author.username)  # lazy-loads each time

# Good: single JOIN for to-one
posts = Post.query.options(joinedload(Post.author)).all()

# Good: 2 queries for to-many, no cartesian blowup
posts = Post.query.options(selectinload(Post.tags)).all()

# SQLAlchemy Core — query-builder style, no ORM layer
rows = db.session.execute(select(Post).where(Post.published == True)).scalars().all()$escape$,
  $escape$python$escape$,
