INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '8d7c0dcb-e94b-4217-b315-2fd5a4ad3db3',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Flask Error Handling — Global Handlers and Consistent Error Responses$escape$,
  $escape$Flask's `@app.errorhandler` decorator lets you intercept exceptions application-wide, keeping error logic out of individual routes. Register handlers by HTTP status code or exception class — Flask will match the most specific one first.

For a consistent API, define a single `make_error` helper that always returns the same JSON shape: `status`, `code`, and `message`. Register handlers for `HTTPException` (covers all Werkzeug-raised 4xx/5xx errors) and a catch-all `Exception` handler for unhandled runtime errors. The `HTTPException` base class exposes `.code` and `.description`, so you can forward those directly.

Critical detail: the catch-all `Exception` handler fires *before* Flask's built-in `HTTPException` handler unless you explicitly check with `isinstance`. Always re-raise or delegate `HTTPException` instances from your generic handler, otherwise a 404 becomes a 500.

In testing, `app.test_client()` returns the full JSON body, so you can assert the shape in unit tests without mocking the error path — just hit a bad route.$escape$,
  $escape$from flask import Flask, jsonify
from werkzeug.exceptions import HTTPException

app = Flask(__name__)

def make_error(status: int, code: str, message: str):
    return jsonify({"status": status, "code": code, "message": message}), status

@app.errorhandler(HTTPException)
def handle_http(e: HTTPException):
    return make_error(e.code, e.name.upper().replace(" ", "_"), e.description)

@app.errorhandler(Exception)
def handle_generic(e: Exception):
    if isinstance(e, HTTPException):
        return handle_http(e)
    app.logger.exception(e)
    return make_error(500, "INTERNAL_ERROR", "An unexpected error occurred")$escape$,
  $escape$python$escape$,
