INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'cd21fd0c-ba42-444f-9328-0f5c658ccd8b',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Flask Has No Batteries — Here's How to Wire Them Yourself$escape$,
  $escape$Unlike Django, Flask ships with almost nothing beyond routing and request handling. No ORM, no admin panel, no form validation, no auth. That's a feature, not a bug — but it means you're assembling the stack yourself.

The canonical Flask extension ecosystem fills these gaps: Flask-SQLAlchemy for ORM, Flask-Migrate for Alembic migrations, Flask-Login for session-based auth, and WTForms for form validation. Auto-docs don't exist natively — you reach for Flask-RESTX or Flasgger to generate Swagger UI from docstrings or decorators.

The critical pattern is the Application Factory (`create_app()`). Instead of instantiating `app = Flask(__name__)` at module level, you defer it inside a function. This lets you swap configs per environment, avoid circular imports when extensions reference `app`, and spin up multiple app instances in tests.

Extensions are initialized against `None` first (`db = SQLAlchemy()`), then bound to the app inside `create_app()` via `db.init_app(app)`. This two-phase init is Flask's substitute for Django's settings-driven auto-configuration.$escape$,
  $escape$from flask import Flask
from flask_sqlalchemy import SQLAlchemy
from flask_migrate import Migrate

db = SQLAlchemy()
migrate = Migrate()

def create_app(config_object="config.ProductionConfig"):
    app = Flask(__name__)
    app.config.from_object(config_object)

    db.init_app(app)
    migrate.init_app(app, db)

    from .routes import bp
    app.register_blueprint(bp)

    return app$escape$,
  $escape$python$escape$,
